## 9. Metrics and Evaluation (Concepts)

| Metric | Why it matters |
|--------|-----------------|
| Job duration | SLA; right-size DPUs. |
| DPU-minutes | Cost per run. |
| Records read/written | Throughput; validate record_count. |
| Reject count (audit) | Data quality; quarantine growth. |
| Job success rate | Reliability. |

**Design choices that sound solid:** Explicit path from job args when one-file-per-run; idempotency at orchestrator; schema + business rules with quarantine and reject reason; staging then commit for writes; audit update only if PENDING.

---

## 10. One-Page Recap (Concepts to Retain)

1. **Glue:** Managed Spark (PySpark); pay per DPU-minute; no cluster to manage. Good for file-based, event-triggered or scheduled batch.
2. **ETL in such a design:** Extract from S3 → Transform in Glue (validate, quarantine bad rows) → Load to curated S3, Kafka, audit. ELT = load raw first, transform in warehouse.
3. **Why Glue over Lambda:** Large files need distributed processing; Glue provides managed Spark.
4. **Job args:** input_path, file_type, file_date from orchestrator; `getResolvedOptions` in script. One-file-per-run → path from args; idempotency at orchestrator + audit.
5. **Validation:** Schema + business rules; valid → curated + Kafka; invalid → quarantine + reason; record_count/reject_count in audit.
6. **Curated write:** Staging prefix then move to final partition. Audit update with condition (only if PENDING).
7. **Spark = execution:** Same PySpark APIs; Glue adds job args, DPUs, catalog, bookmarks.

